(7, 8, 2, NULL, 0, 0, 'uploads/custom-images/blogs/image-2024-05-19-09-03-02-2646.jpg', 'Bittersweet Beauty: Forging Friendships Overseas', '<p>It\'s been nearly two months since my return, and the recurring word that resonates with this experience is simply \'weird.\' Everything feels weird. I find myself pondering over the reverse culture shock: why are there so many choices in stores? Why is everything so large and loud? And why do I possess so much stuff? The reality of engaging in Dutch bingo in my small hometown is unsettling, while the campus feels eerily deserted in the summer. It\'s challenging to figure out how to convey months of abroad experiences to my family. On the flip side, there are plenty of beautiful moments being back: my Dad\'s homemade breakfasts, playing with my younger siblings in the yard, reuniting with old friends, riding my horses again, celebrating Mother\'s Day, witnessing Lake Michigan sunsets, and embarking on countless trips \'up north.\' However, rather than dwelling on the present, I find myself yearning to rewind further back, to take you along on a journey to a quaint town in northern France, with a very special friend I met in Liverpool.</p><p><br></p><p>If you\'ve been following my posts, you\'re likely familiar with Romane. She started as my flatmate and hiking companion, but quickly evolved into much more. After feeling somewhat overwhelmed and out of place following the initial orientation at LHU, I longed for the familiarity of my friends from Hope and the effortless passage of time we shared. Amidst the vibrant crowd in Liverpool, I prayed for a unique connection. Remarkably, the very next morning, while clumsily making breakfast, I unintentionally set the toaster on fire, disrupting the morning routine of the sweet French girl down the hall. We managed to extinguish the flames, coughed through the smoke, summoned the security guard, and chuckled all the way to campus on the bus. And so, our friendship blossomed from the chaos of burnt toast, damaged appliances, and a scolding from a Scouser.&nbsp;</p><p><br></p><p>This post has been lingering unfinished for two months now (I can\'t believe it!), and the consequence of my procrastination is that instead of completing it on a train or in a hostel on the continent, I find myself nestled next to my little sister on the couch in our home in Saugatuck. The evening breeze carries the serenade of crickets and the distant hum of semis on the highway through the screen door. I\'m home.</p><p><br></p><p><br></p>', 1, '2024-05-19 16:03:02', '2024-05-19 16:43:07');
